This not only confirms that some dinosaurs had feathers, a widely held theory, but also provides more detail than fossils, such as colour and three-dimensional arrangement.
According to scientists, the plumage of this animal was brownish-brown in the upper part, with a pale or carotenoid coloration in the lower part.
The discovery also provides detailed information on the evolution of bird feathers.
Because dinosaur plumage lacks the basic structure, called the tail, but instead has other features typical of feathers, beards, and barbels, researchers have concluded that the tail is likely the result of a successive evolutionary development of these characteristics.
The structure of the plumage suggests that it was not used for flight, but rather for temperature regulation or courtship.
According to the hypothesis of the researchers, despite the coda belonging to a young dinosaur, the specimen reveals a plumage of an adult specimen and not that of a chick.
